**Five core properties**

**Transfers via mint.** `push(address)` sends 1 unit directly to any recipient. There is no transfer function because there needs to be none. Sending is minting.

**Resistant to key compromise.** If quantum computing or any future exploit breaks ECDSA key security, there is nothing to drain — no ETH, no transferable asset. A compromised key grants an attacker your push count. The legacy system lets you migrate to a new address immediately and carry your full history forward.

**Cannot be stolen or seized.** No ETH is held. No admin key exists. No owner can be compelled. No transfer function can be exploited. No DEX liquidity can be drained. Your activity record is visible to all and controllable by none.

**No speculation by design.** No transfer function means no secondary market mechanism exists in the contract. No DEX integration, no ETH value, decimals at zero. The contract provides no infrastructure for speculation.

**Permissionless and passwordless.** No signup. No seed phrase. No company. No recovery email. Anyone calls `push()`. Recovery itself is permissionless — any new address can claim any old address at any time, from any point after the key was lost.

